<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1806,2014]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,1878,1904]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species can be easily identified from the other species of the family occurring in the freshwaters of the country (Pacific side) by the coloration pattern [eye-side brown, with faint, thin dark crossbars and dots; dorsal and anal fins dark brown; caudal fin light yellow; blind-side light grey-brown (anterior half) to dark grey-brown (posterior half); see 
<bibRefCitation author="Krupp, F." box="[376,528,1986,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="845 - 850" refId="ref65010" refString="Krupp, F. (1995) Achiridae. In: Fischer, W., Krupp, F., Schneider, W., Sommer, C. &amp; Carpenter, K. E. (Eds.), Guia FAO para la identificacion de especies para los fines de la pesca: Pacifico centro-oriental. FAO, Rome, pp. 845 - 850." type="book chapter" year="1995">Krupp (1995)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Robertson, D. R. &amp; Allen, G. R." box="[581,878,1986,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" refId="ref66239" refString="Robertson, D. R. &amp; Allen, G. R. (2015) Shorefishes of the Tropical Eastern Pacific: online information system. Version 2.0. Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Balboa, Panama. Available from: https: // biogeodb. stri. si. edu / sftep / en / pages (accessed 27 August 2021)." type="url" year="2015">Robertson &amp; Allen (2015)</bibRefCitation>
].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
